<!-- Per MOS:BOLDTITLE and WP:SBE, neither the article's title nor related text appears in bold. -->An ongoing hostage crisis began on 15 December 2014 in [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]], Australia. A lone gunman,<ref name="5 people flee Sydney hostage-crisis building">{{cite web|url=http://www.wral.com/major-police-operation-unfolding-in-sydney/14279135/|title=5 people escape Sydney cafe in hostage crisis|author=WRAL|work=WRAL.com|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> later identified by police as [[Sheikh Haron]],<ref name=age-Monis/><ref name=abc-Monis/> entered a [[Lindt & Sprüngli|Lindt]] chocolate cafe located at [[Martin Place, Sydney|Martin Place]] and remains inside holding employees and customers hostage. After several hours, five of the hostages escaped, while an unknown number remained inside the building.<ref name="Police negotiate with gunman after five people emerge" />  

Hostages were seen holding up a black [[Black Standard#Jihadist black flag|Islamic flag]] with the Arabic ''[[shahada|shahādah]]''.<ref name="Seven in 'lockdown' due to hostage crisis">{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/national/breaking-news/seven-evacuates-newsroom-near-cafe-siege/story-e6frfku9-1227156337550|title=Seven in 'lockdown' due to hostage crisis|work=NewsComAu|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> The gunman is "claiming political motivation".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Griffiths |first1=Emma |title=Sydney siege: Prime Minister Tony Abbott says gunman is 'claiming political motivation'|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-12-15/abbott-says-it-is-unclear-if-sydney-siege-politically-motivated/5967860|accessdate=15 December 2014|agency=ABC News|publisher=ABC News|date=15 December 2014<!--8pm Perth time-->}}</ref><ref name="Gunman 'with a political motivation' holds hostages in Sydney, Australia" />

As a result of the siege, road closures were implemented in the [[Sydney central business district]], the area around the siege site was closed to the public and some nearby government buildings locked down.<ref name=businessinsider-happening /> On 16 December 2014, police stormed the cafe.<ref name=abc-blog /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-australia-30485355|title=Sydney cafe siege: Australia police storm building|date=15 December 2014|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>

==Event==
[[File:Martin-place-lindt.jpg|thumb|The Lindt Chocolate Café where the crisis is taking place, pictured in 2013]]
The crisis began at the [[Lindt & Sprüngli#Lindt Chocolat Café|Lindt Chocolate Café]] in 53 Martin Place, Sydney, at 9:44 a.m. [[Australian Eastern Daylight Time|AEDT]] (22:44 [[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]]) on 15 December. Hostages were seen holding up a [[Black Standard#Jihadist black flag|jihadist black flag]] with the Arabic ''[[shahada|shahādah]]'' "There is no God but Allah and Muhammad is the messenger of God".<ref name=smhlindt1>[http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/lindt-chocolat-cafe-hostage-drama-in-martin-place-sydney-20141215-1278cx.html "Lindt Chocolate Cafe Hostage Drama in Martin Place Sydney."] ''Sydney Morning Herald''. 15 December 2014.</ref><ref name="Seven in 'lockdown' due to hostage crisis" /> The flag was initially mistaken as a flag for the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] in news reports.<ref name="Gunman 'with a political motivation' holds hostages in Sydney, Australia">{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/world/asia/la-fg-major-police-operation-sydney-20141214-story.html#page=1|title=Police say they are in contact with gunman holding hostages in Sydney, Australia|work=news|accessdate=15 December 2014<!-- 8:40pm Perth time-->}}</ref> One of the hostages was reportedly being used as a [[human shield]] by the gunman,<ref>Rolling coverage on [[Seven News]] ([[ATN]]), ''[[Seven West Media]]'', 15 December 2014.</ref> who was later described as bearded, wearing a white shirt and a black [[bandana]], and armed with a [[shotgun]].<ref name="LIVE STREAM: Gunman forcing hostages to stand against cafe windows in Sydney siege" /><ref name="Gunman 'with a political motivation' holds hostages in Sydney, Australia" /> Prior to the siege, the automatic sliding doors of the cafe were disabled.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2014/12/15/siege-sydneys-martin-place-cafe|title=Sydney siege: Hostages held at Martin Place cafe|work=News|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref><ref name="Sydney Hostage Crisis: Dozens Held Inside Cafe, Islamic Flag Put Up on Window">{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/world/sydney-hostage-crisis-dozens-held-inside-cafe-islamic-flag-put-up-on-window-634572|title=Sydney Hostage Crisis: Dozens Held Inside Cafe, Islamic Flag Put Up on Window|work=NDTV.com|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref>

According to [[2GB|Sydney 2GB]] radio announcer [[Ray Hadley]], the gunman demanded to speak to the Prime Minister live on radio, although these reports are unconfirmed.<ref name="sunshinelindt1">[http://www.sunshinecoastdaily.com.au/news/breaking-hostages-taken-sydney-cafe/2484985/ "Hostage crisis: First images of 'lead gunman.'"] ''Sunshine Coast Daily''</ref> There were also further reports that the gunman stated that there were four "devices" located around Sydney. However, New South Wales Police Commissioner [[Andrew Scipione]] stated that none of the alleged "devices" were found during investigations.<ref name="Abbott speaks to nation: We won't let them scare us">{{cite web|url=http://www.gympietimes.com.au/news/breaking-hostages-taken-sydney-cafe/2484985/|title=Five hostages flee in terror from Sydney hostage drama|date=15 December 2014|work=Gympie Times|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> Two female hostages made contact with media outlets and relayed the gunman's demands to them, but the New South Wales Police Force requested that the demands not be published.<ref name="SMH Police clear Martin Place">{{cite news|last1=Levy|first1=Megan|last2=Begley|first2=Patrick|title=Police clear Martin Place after gunman holds hostages at Lindt Chocolat Cafe|url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/police-clear-martin-place-after-gunman-holds-hostages-at-lindt-chocolat-cafe-20141215-127824.html|accessdate=15 December 2014|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=15 December 2014}}</ref><ref name="Gunman 'with a political motivation' holds hostages in Sydney, Australia" />

[[New South Wales Police Force|New South Wales Police]] treated the event as a terrorist attack.<ref name=smh-terrorist>{{cite news|last1=Ralston|first1=Nick|last2=Partridge|first2=Emma|title=Martin Place siege being treated as terrorist attack, police confirm|url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/martin-place-siege-being-treated-as-terrorist-attack-police-confirm-20141215-127mh5.html|accessdate=15 December 2014|work=Sydney Morning Herald|date=15 December 2014}}</ref> Police were negotiating with the gunman throughout the day.<ref name=abc-know>{{cite news|title=Sydney siege: What we do and don't know about hostage situation in Martin Place|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-12-15/sydney-siege-what-we-know/5967610|accessdate=15 December 2014|work=ABC News|publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation|date=15 December 2014}}</ref>

NSW Police Deputy Commissioner Catherine Burn confirmed that around 3:37 p.m., two hostages emerged from the front entrance of the building, followed by a third hostage, an employee, who ran out from a fire exit at the side of the building. Media outlets advised that the hostages were not released, but had escaped, though details were not immediately available.<ref name="LIVE STREAM: Gunman forcing hostages to stand against cafe windows in Sydney siege" /><ref name="Lindt Chocolat Cafe hostage drama in Martin Place, Sydney">{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/nsw/lindt-chocolat-cafe-hostage-drama-in-martin-place-sydney-20141215-1278cx.html|title=Lindt Chocolat Cafe hostage drama in Martin Place, Sydney|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> It was later confirmed by police that all three hostages escaped.<ref name="Police confirm three people escape Sydney cafe where gunman holds hostages">{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2014/12/15/hostage-situation-reportedly-unfolding-in-sydney-chocolate-shop/|title=Sydney siege: Police in contact with gunman as five hostages escape|work=Fox News|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> At around 4:58 p.m., two female hostages, both employees, ran from another entrance of the building, having also escaped,<ref name="LIVE STREAM: Gunman forcing hostages to stand against cafe windows in Sydney siege" /> and were met by officers with the [[State Protection Group|Tactical Operations Unit]].<ref name="LIVE STREAM: Gunman forcing hostages to stand against cafe windows in Sydney siege" /><ref name="5 people flee Sydney hostage-crisis building" />

At 2:08 a.m. on 16 December, a group of five hostages ran out of the building, followed by another hostage. Minutes later, heavily armed police stormed the cafe amidst loud bangs and flashes of light, following which further hostages were rescued from the building.<ref name=abc-blog />

===Hostages===
[[File:2014 Sydney hostage crisis 01.jpg|thumb|Police blocking Martin Place near Lindt cafe]]

It was initially estimated that there were 13 people inside. Subsequent to the debriefing of the escaped hostages, authorities advised that no more than 10 hostages remained inside the cafe.<ref name="LIVE STREAM: Gunman forcing hostages to stand against cafe windows in Sydney siege" />

One of the escaped hostages was hospitalised for a pre-existing condition<ref>{{cite news|title=Press conference with NSW Police Chief Commissioner Scipione|accessdate=15 December 2014|work=ABC News|date=15 December 2014}}</ref> and was in a satisfactory condition.<ref name="Gunman 'with a political motivation' holds hostages in Sydney, Australia" />

[[File:2014 Sydney hostage crisis, Martin Place.ogv|thumb|Martin Place video]]
==Effects==
[[File:2014-hostage-crisis-openstreetmap.svg|thumb|right|Map indicating the location of the hostage situation]]

===Transportation===
Trains were not stopping at [[Martin Place railway station]] due to the hostage situation. [[Transport New South Wales]] advised people to stay away from the CBD.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.transportnsw.info/en/transport-status/alerts-detail.page?MessageNum=2011749&type=train|title=Transport status alert - transportnsw.info|publisher=|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> Road closures also occurred. There is no southbound access to the [[Cahill Expressway]], [[York Street, Sydney|York Street]], or Harbour Street. There is no northbound access to the Cahill Expressway, and all traffic is being diverted to the [[Sydney Harbour Tunnel]]. Northbound traffic on the Western Distributor is being diverted over Sydney Harbour Bridge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-12-15/sydney-siege-leads-to-cbd-transport-closures/5967700|title=Sydney siege: Martin Place Lindt cafe hostage situation leads to road closures and transport diversions|work=ABC News|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> Various road closures are in place.<ref name=businessinsider-happening>{{cite news|last1=Thomsen|first1=Simon|title=SYDNEY SIEGE: Here's What's Happening To The City As A Result|url=http://www.businessinsider.com.au/sydney-siege-update-heres-whats-happening-to-the-city-as-a-result-2014-12|accessdate=15 December 2014|work=Business Insider Australia|date=15 December 2014}}</ref>

[[Uber (company)|Uber Sydney]]'s automatic pricing led to people leaving the city being charged a minimum of $100 during the siege. After public outcry, Uber announced on its [[Twitter]] profile that trips from Sydney's central business district "will be free for riders"; however, surge pricing into the CBD was retained to attract drivers.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Brian Ries, Jenni Ryall|title=Uber introduces surge pricing in downtown Sydney during hostage siege|url=http://mashable.com/2014/12/14/uber-sydney-surge-pricing/#:eyJzIjoidCIsImkiOiJfamYxa2phYmt2cXZqdHNtNSJ9|website=Mashable|publisher=Mashable|accessdate=15 December 2014|date=15 December 2014}}</ref>

===Evacuations and closures===
[[File:Sydney hostage crisis - Road closures.jpg|thumb|Road closures]]

Immediately after the siege began, people found above the cafe were evacuated by ladder.<ref>[http://livenews.abc.net.au/Event/Live_blog_Siege_in_Sydneys_Martin_Place/137067049 Police have evacuated people trapped in the buildi... - ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation)<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The [[Sydney Opera House]] was evacuated after a suspicious package was found, however reports were unconfirmed by police.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sky.com/story/1391970/sydney-siege-up-to-20-hostages-held-reports|title=Sydney Siege: Up To 20 Hostages Held - Reports|work=Sky News|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://tvnz.co.nz/world-news/sydney-opera-house-evacuated-after-reports-suspicious-package-6206406|title = Sydney Opera House evacuated after reports of a suspicious package|date = 15 December 2014|accessdate = 15 December 2014|website = |publisher = TVNZ|last = |first = }}</ref> The U.S. Consulate General in Sydney, located in Martin Place, was also evacuated.<ref>{{cite news|title=US Consulate in Sydney near hostage cafe crisis evacuated, security warning issued|url=http://www.stasiareport.com/news/asia/australianew-zealand/story/us-consulate-sydney-near-hostage-cafe-crisis-evacuated-security|accessdate=14 December 2014|work=The Straits Times|publisher=Singapore Press Holdings Ltd|date=15 December 2014}}</ref>

Police advised people in the area bounded by [[Hunter Street, Sydney|Hunter]], [[King Street, Sydney|George]], [[Elizabeth Street, Sydney|Elizabeth]], and [[Macquarie Street, Sydney|Macquarie Streets]], bordering Martin Place, to remain indoors and away from windows.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/nswpolice/status/544303006460551168/photo/1|title=NSW Police on Twitter|work=Twitter|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> [[Commonwealth Bank]], [[Westpac]], and [[Australia and New Zealand Banking Group]] have closed their CBD branches for today.<ref name=abc-blog /> The [[State Library of New South Wales]] has also closed its doors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/statelibrarynsw/status/544286317698248704|title=State Library of NSW on Twitter|work=Twitter|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> Numerous other buildings, including [[David Jones Limited]] stores, executive offices for the [[New South Wales Parliament]], criminal courts for the [[New South Wales Supreme Court]], the [[Downing Centre]], and "several city legal chambers" have been evacuated.<ref>[http://smhcom.freetrialoffer.us/nsw/police-clear-martin-place-after-gunman-holds-hostages-at-lindt-chocolat-cafe-20141215-127824.html Police clear Martin Place after gunman holds hostages at Lindt Chocolat Cafe<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> The facilities of the [[Seven Network]], which is situated directly across from the cafe, are under lockdown.<ref name="7lockdown">{{Cite news|url = http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/latest-news/seven-evacuates-newsroom-near-cafe-siege/story-fn3dxiwe-1227156337550?nk=c384aa539f9733e57b7ea166dbe4d3aa|title = Seven in 'lockdown' due to hostage crisis|last = |first = |date = 15 December 2014|work = The Australian|accessdate = 15 December 2014|newspaper = }}</ref>

Some Sydney schools were put in "white level lockout" due to the hostage crisis, which means that no school group may leave the school grounds.<ref name=smhlindt1/>

==Hostage taker==
The hostage taker has been identified as Iranian-born [[Man Haron Monis]]. He is a self-proclaimed [[sheikh]], although he is not recognised as such in the Islamic community.<ref name=age-Monis>{{cite news|last1=Ralston|first1=Nick|title=Martin Place, Sydney siege gunman identified as Man Haron Monis|url=http://www.theage.com.au/nsw/martin-place-sydney-siege-gunman-identified-as-man-haron-monis-20141215-127sxt.html|accessdate=15 December 2014|work=[[The Age]]}}</ref><ref name=abc-Monis>{{cite news|last1=Knowles|first1=Lorna|title=Sydney siege: Man behind siege named as Iranian cleric Man Haron Monis|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-12-16/cleric/5969246|accessdate=15 December 2014|work=ABC News|date=16 December 2014}}</ref>

He has a history of legal problems. He protested the presence of Australian troops in [[War in Afghanistan (2001–present)|Afghanistan]], by writing letters to the families of soldiers killed there, in which he called the soldiers murderers<ref>{{cite news|author=AAP|date=6 September 2013|title=Sheik says letters were flowers of advice|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2013/09/06/sheik-says-letters-were-flowers-advice|work=SBS News|publisher=sbs.com.au|accessdate=8 February 2014}}</ref> and urged the soldiers' families to petition the government to remove its troops from Afghanistan; one of the letters compared a deceased soldier to a pig and called his body "contaminated".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.humanrights.gov.au/publications/casenote-monis-v-queen-2013-hca-4-1|title=Casenote: Monis v The Queen [2013] HCA 4|work=humanrights.gov.au|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref>  Haron was arrested on charges of "using a postal or similar service to menace, harass or cause offence".<ref>{{cite news|last=Hoerr|first=Karl|date=22 November 2013|title='Hate mail' suspect protests against 'misinterpretation'|url=http://www.abc.net.au/lateline/content/2008/s2739013.htm|work=Lateline|publisher=abc.net.au|accessdate=8 February 2014}}</ref> In 2013 he was charged with being an accessory to the murder of his ex-wife, allegedly stabbed and set alight in a stairwell on 21 April 2013. His partner, Amirah Droudis, was formally charged with Pal's murder.<ref>{{cite news|author=AAP|date=22 November 2013|title=Self-styled Muslim sheikh faces court on accessory to murder charge|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2013-11-22/self-styled-muslim-sheikh-faces-court-on-accessory-to-murder-ch/5111744|work=ABC News|publisher=abc.net.au|accessdate=8 February 2014}}</ref>

On 14 March 2014, Haron was arrested and charged with sexually and indecently assaulting a young woman who went to his consultancy in [[Wentworthville, New South Wales]] for "spiritual healing", after seeing an advertisement in a local newspaper. Haron claimed he was an expert in "astrology, numerology, meditation and black magic" services.<ref>{{cite news|author=ABC News|date=14 April 2014|title='Spiritual healer' refused bail over alleged 2002 sexual assaults at Wentworthville in Sydney's west|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-04-14/spiritual-healer-arrested-for-sexual-assault/5388332|work=ABC News|publisher=abc.net.au|accessdate=14 April 2014}}</ref>

He posted to his website earlier in December 2014 this message: "I used to be a [[Rafidi]], but not any more. Now I am a Muslim, ''[[Alhamdu Lillah]]''".<ref name=age-Monis/> "Rafidi" is a derogatory term used by [[Salafi|Salafis]] to describe the [[Shia]] branch of Islam.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=azCRjNPFdgQC&pg=PA141&dq=salafi+derogatory+rafidi&hl=en&sa=X&ei=9vmOVOaQMND9yQSdhIKoDA&ved=0CBwQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=salafi%20derogatory%20rafidi&f=false|title=A Quietist Jihadi|publisher=|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref>

==Reactions==

===Government===
Australian [[Prime Minister of Australia|Prime Minister]] [[Tony Abbott]] convened the National Security Committee of Cabinet to give briefings on the situation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/news/update/2014-12-15/abbott-reassures-australians-over-sydney-siege/|title=Abbott reassures Australians over Sydney siege|work=ITV News|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://forums.pmc.gov.au/media|title=Incident in Martin Place, Sydney|work=Prime Minister of Australia Media|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=smhlindt1 /> Abbott made a public statement reassuring Australians, stating, "Australians should be reassured that our law enforcement and security agencies are well trained and equipped and are responding in a thorough and professional manner."<ref name="Hostages Taken at Australian Chocolate Shop">{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/news/world/hostages-taken-australian-chocolate-shop-n268321|title=Five Hostages Flee Lindt Chocolate Cafe in Sydney, Australia|work=NBC News|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> He later said, "The whole point of politically-motivated violence is to scare people out of being themselves. Australia is a peaceful, open, and generous society. Nothing should ever change that and that's why I would urge all Australians today to go about their business as usual."<ref name="Abbott speaks to nation: We won't let them scare us" />

[[Premier of New South Wales|New South Wales Premier]] [[Mike Baird]] addressed the media, stating "We are being tested today... in Sydney. The police are being tested, the public is being tested, but whatever the test we will face it head on and we will remain a strong democratic, civil society. I have full confidence in the Police Commissioner and the incredible work of the NSW police force."<ref name=abc-blog /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QXYrHlBPX-k&feature=youtu.be|title=Premier and Commissioner address the media re: Martin Place police operation|work=YouTube|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref>

===Community===
Due to concerns about anti-[[muslim]] backlash and attacks, a grassroots movement named ''#illridewithyou'' was started on social media in order to physically and emotionally support Muslims traveling alone on public transport.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/technology/online/illridewithyou-twitter-sprouts-anti-islamophobia-campaign/story-fnjwnhzf-1227157197523|title=#illridewithyou: Twitter sprouts anti-Islamophobia campaign|publisher=[[news.com.au]]|date=15 December 2014|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theage.com.au/nsw/martin-place-siege-illridewithyou-hashtag-goes-viral-20141215-127rm1.html|title=Martin Place siege: #illridewithyou hashtag goes viral|publisher=[[Sydney Morning Herald]]|date=15 December 2014|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-12-15/illridewithyou-hashtag-takes-off-following-siege/5969102|title = #illridewithyou: support for Muslim Australians takes off following Sydney siege|last = |first = |date = 15 December 2014|work = ABC News|accessdate = 15 December 2014}}</ref>

===Muslim organisations===
Sanier Dandan, the president of the [[Lebanese Muslim Association]], informed [[ABC News (Australia)|ABC News]] that Australian Muslim leaders were meeting online for discussions on how the Muslim community could help with the crisis. He also added that it was not known if the perpetrator or perpetrators were linked to the Australian Muslim community, saying, "Regardless we have a hostage situation. Whether he is someone who belongs to the Australian Muslim community or not, we are still waiting for information to be provided by police and based on that if there's something the Muslim community can do or assist, we are there."<ref name="Sydney hostage crisis: Live Report">{{cite web|url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/news/world/449935/sydney-hostage-crisis-live-report|title=Sydney hostage crisis: Live Report|author=Post Publishing PCL.|work=http://www.bangkokpost.com|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref><ref name="businessinsider-live">{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/afp-sydney-hostage-crisis-live-report-2014-12|title=Sydney hostage crisis: Live Report - Business Insider|date=15 December 2014|work=Business Insider|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> Ibrahim Abu Mohamed, the [[Grand Mufti]] of Australia, also condemned the incident in a released statement.<ref name=abc-blog /><ref name="Central Sydney Is in Lockdown Amid a Developing Hostage Crisis">{{cite news|url=http://time.com/3633134/sydney-hostage-martin-place-lindt-cafe-terrorism/|title=Sydney Hostage Crisis: Major Police Operation Unfolding|work=TIME.com|accessdate=15 December 2014}}</ref> During the afternoon of 15 December around 50 Muslim groups issued a joint statement in which they condemned the incident.<ref name=abc-blog>{{cite news|last1=Franklin|first1=Daniel|title=Live blog: Siege in Sydney's Martin Place|url=http://livenews.abc.net.au/Event/Live_blog_Siege_in_Sydneys_Martin_Place/137083674|accessdate=15 December 2014|work=ABC News|date=15 December 2014}}</ref>

